<subSubSection id="C30A6567FFBEF72AFCB469AEFDBBE646" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="518" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BAF36ECFFBEF72AFCB469AEFDBBE646" blockId="10.[806,1421,1667,1903]" lastBlockId="11.[164,779,198,557]" lastPageId="11" lastPageNumber="518" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBEF72BFCB469AEFC5CE2F3" box="[806,925,1667,1688]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Diagnosis:</emphasis>
Two species are included in the subgenus 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D6FFFBEF72BFCB4698FFC5FE2DC" box="[806,926,1698,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Grammia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subGenus" subGenus="Mimarctia">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBEF72BFCB4698FFC5FE2DC" box="[806,926,1698,1719]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Mimarctia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D6FFFBEF72BFC26698FFBA2E2DC" authorityName="Conner, Webster &amp; Itagaki" authorityYear="1985" baseAuthorityName="Drury" box="[948,1123,1698,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Grammia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="arge">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBEF72BFC26698FFBA2E2DC" box="[948,1123,1698,1719]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Grammia arge</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D6FFFBEF72BFB3E698FFACFE2DD" baseAuthorityName="Boisduval" baseAuthorityYear="1869" box="[1196,1294,1697,1719]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Grammia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="doris">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBEF72BFB3E698FFACFE2DD" box="[1196,1294,1697,1719]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">G. doris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Although the wing pattern is superficially much like other 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D6FFFBEF72BFCB469F2FC55E29F" authorityName="Rambur" authorityYear="1866" box="[806,916,1759,1780]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Grammia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="10" pageNumber="517" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBEF72BFCB469F2FC55E29F" box="[806,916,1759,1780]" italics="true" pageId="10" pageNumber="517">Grammia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the forewing costal cell is entirely palescaled (except sometimes at extreme base), and the costal portion of the postmedial band is angled sharply basad, forming a straight or nearly straight line with the anal portion of the subterminal band (Figs 4, 5). Structurally, the dorsal margin of the male juxta is deeply cleft, v-shaped to slightly u-shaped, with a medial groove extending ventrally; the diverticula of the male vesica are much larger and more elongate than in any other 
<taxonomicName id="4C104D6FFFBFF72AFDA16E6CFCCBE53D" box="[563,778,320,342]" class="Insecta" family="Arctiidae" genus="Grammia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="11" pageNumber="518" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="undetermined">
<emphasis id="B964EAFEFFBFF72AFDA16E6CFD60E53D" box="[563,673,321,342]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="518">Grammia</emphasis>
species
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation id="132B2A69FFBFF72AFF3E6E72FE93E51E" box="[172,338,351,373]" captionStart="Figures 40–45" captionStartId="73.[164,254,1744,1763]" captionTargetBox="[226,1383,197,1711]" captionTargetId="figure-0@73.[224,1386,194,1714]" captionTargetPageId="73" captionText="Figures 40–45. Genitalia of male Holarctia and Grammia, ventral aspect of valve (a) and right lateral aspect of aedeagus (b) (scale bar = 1 mm). 40, Holarctia obliterata (Stretch). 41, Grammia arge (Drury). 42, Grammia doris doris (Bdv.). 43, Grammia phyllira (Drury). 44, Grammia placentia (J. E. Smith). 45, Grammia virgo virgo (L.)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5444725" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5444725/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="518">Figs 41B, 42B</figureCitation>
). The female ductus bursae lacks the sclerotized lateral plates (
<figureCitation id="132B2A69FFBFF72AFE5D6E50FD91E5FF" box="[463,592,381,404]" captionStart="Figures 72–78" captionStartId="79.[164,254,1648,1667]" captionTargetBox="[227,1380,201,1616]" captionTargetId="figure-0@79.[225,1383,196,1619]" captionTargetPageId="79" captionText="Figures 72–78. Genitalia of female Grammia, ventral aspect (scale bar = 1 mm). 72, Grammia arge (Drury). 73, Grammia doris doris (Bdv.). 74, Grammia obliterata (Stretch). 75, Grammia phyllira (Drury). 76, Grammia placentia (J. E. Smith). 77, Grammia virgo (L.). 78, Grammia parthenice (Kby.)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5444737" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5444737/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="518">Figs 72, 73</figureCitation>
). The cremaster of the pupa is elongate, with well-developed longitudinal folds not extending onto distal portion of cremaster (
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B1DFFBFF72AFE916EF4FE5EE584" author="Smith ME" box="[259,415,473,495]" pageId="11" pageNumber="518" refId="ref64404" refString="Smith ME. 1938 a. A revision of the genus Apantesis Walker (Lepidoptera, Arctiidae). Unpublished Ph. D. thesis. Urbana: University of Illinois." type="book" year="1938">Smith, 1938a</bibRefCitation>
). The larvae have a complete or partial subdorsal stripe, and the tubercles are dull with finely barbed setae (
<bibRefCitation id="EF814B1DFFBFF72AFE426D3BFDAFE646" author="Smith ME" box="[464,622,534,557]" pageId="11" pageNumber="518" refId="ref64404" refString="Smith ME. 1938 a. A revision of the genus Apantesis Walker (Lepidoptera, Arctiidae). Unpublished Ph. D. thesis. Urbana: University of Illinois." type="book" year="1938">Smith, 1938a</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
